Please produce customer meeting notes using the following structure. Be thorough — extract every detail from the transcript.

## Title
[A short, descriptive title — 3 to 10 words capturing the main topic. Be specific about the customer and subject.]

## Summary
[2-4 sentences: who the customer is, what was discussed, key outcomes, and any critical issues or wins]

## Detailed Notes
[A comprehensive narrative write-up of the customer meeting (~400–1200 words). Walk through the conversation in the order it unfolded: how the meeting opened, what the customer emphasized, how their concerns or questions evolved, and how our side responded. Capture the reasoning, nuance, and context behind requirements and feedback — not just the items themselves. Attribute positions to named participants (customer and our team) where clear. Include concrete details: product/service names, numbers, dates, environments, specific pain points. Use subheadings, paragraphs, and bullets for readability. Do not duplicate the structured lists below verbatim — weave the narrative around them. Only include information actually present in the transcript.]

## Customer Background & Context
[Who is the customer, their industry, their current environment, and why this meeting was held. Include account status and relationship context if mentioned.]

## Customer Requirements & Requests
[Specific requirements, feature requests, or asks from the customer. Be precise — include timelines, priorities, and any conditions mentioned.]

## Service Feedback
[Capture ALL feedback the customer shared about services they use. This is critical intelligence.]

### AWS Services Feedback
[Customer feedback on any AWS services (EC2, S3, Lambda, EKS, SageMaker, Bedrock, Control Tower, Security Hub, IAM, CloudFormation, etc.). Include: satisfaction level, pain points, feature requests, performance issues, cost concerns, comparison with alternatives. If not discussed, write "Not discussed".]

### NetApp Services Feedback
[Customer feedback on any NetApp services (ONTAP, Cloud Volumes, StorageGRID, BlueXP, Astra, FSx for NetApp ONTAP, etc.). Include: satisfaction level, pain points, feature requests, performance issues, cost concerns, migration experiences. If not discussed, write "Not discussed".]

### Other Services & Tools Feedback
[Customer feedback on any other vendor services, tools, or platforms mentioned. If not discussed, write "Not discussed".]

## Customer Blockers
[Identify ALL blockers the customer mentioned. Categorize each precisely:]

### Operational Blockers
[Customer operational issues: service outages they experienced, access/permission problems, tooling failures, deployment difficulties, monitoring gaps, incident response concerns. If none, write "None identified".]

### Organizational Blockers
[Customer organizational issues: internal team alignment, procurement/approval delays, lack of trained staff, unclear ownership of decisions, stakeholder buy-in challenges. If none, write "None identified".]

### Physical / Infrastructure Blockers
[Customer infrastructure issues: data center constraints, network limitations, hardware refresh cycles, hybrid cloud connectivity, data residency requirements, compliance constraints. If none, write "None identified".]

### Roadmap / Strategic Blockers
[Customer strategic concerns: misalignment with vendor roadmap, migration timeline risks, vendor lock-in concerns, technology direction uncertainty, budget constraints affecting long-term plans. If none, write "None identified".]

## Demo / Presentation Notes
[Key points from any demo or presentation. Customer reactions, questions asked, features that resonated, concerns raised.]

## Commitments Made
[Any commitments made by either party. Be explicit about who committed to what and by when.]

### Our Commitments to Customer
[What we promised to deliver or follow up on]

### Customer Commitments
[What the customer agreed to do (provide data, make decisions, schedule follow-ups, etc.)]

## Decisions
[All decisions made during the meeting, with who made them]

## Action Items
[Every follow-up task. Be thorough — capture even informal commitments.]
